    <li class="question">
        A block of mass \( m \) is on a frictionless ramp with angle of incline \( \theta \).
        The surface of the ramp and the block have a coefficient of kinetic friction of \( \mu_k \).
        The block is already moving.
        <br>
        <img src = '/asset/{{id}}/ramp_problems_4.png' height = '200px' width ='auto' />
    <ol class="subQuestionList">
        <li class="subQuestion" data-answer_id = 'fbd2'>
            Draw a free-body diagram for the block in terms
            of \( \theta \), \( g \), \( m \), and \( \mu_k \).
            Do not break any forces into components on the free-body diagram.
        </li>
        <li class="subQuestion" data-answer = '\( \left| \Sigma F \right| = \left| m g \sin \left( \theta \right) - \mu_k m g \cos (\theta) \right| \)'>
            Determine the magnitude of net force acting on the block
            in terms of \( \theta \), \( g \), \( m \), and \( \mu_k \).
            Note that because this questions asks specifically for magnitude
            and not direction, you should write your expression within absolute value signs.
        </li>
        <li class="subQuestion" data-answer = 'The direction of net force is down the ramp is \( \sin(\theta) > \mu_k \cos(\theta) \) but up the ramp if otherwise'>
            The direction of the net force is actually <emph>conditional</emph>.
            State two different possible answers for direction (in words) and the condition of each answer.
        </li>
        <li class="subQuestion" data-answer = 'The block is moving downward, but slowing down.'>
            It is stated in the problem that the block is moving down the ramp.
            What does it mean if the net force is acting up the ramp.
        </li>
        <li class="subQuestion" data-answer = '\( a = g \sin \left( \theta \right) - \mu_k g \cos (\theta)\ \) \text{  down the ramp}'>
            Assuming \( \sin(\theta) > \mu_k \cos(\theta) \).
            determine the magnitude and direction of the acceleration of the block
            in terms of \( \theta \), \( g \), and \( \mu_k \).
        </li>
        <li class="subQuestion" data-answer = 'If \( \mu_k = 0 \), then the frictional force disappears, \( \Sigma F = m g \sin \left( \theta \right) \), and \( a = g \sin \left( \theta \right) \), as in the problem above.'>
            Demonstrate that if \( \mu_k = 0 \),
            the free-body diagram, net force, and acceleration
            are identical to that for a block on a frictionless ramp
            (the previous problem).
        </li>
    </ol>
</ol>

